data.value:
Jupiter is the largest planet in our solar system, by far. In fact, it's more than twice as massive as all the other planets combined! If Jupiter was the size of a basketball, Earth would be about the size of a grape. It's unknown what Jupiters dense core is made of, but we do know that Jupiter’s atmosphere resembles that of the sun, being made up mostly of helium and hydrogen. The white clouds ringing the planet are made of crystals of frozen ammonia, while the composition of the dark clouds is still unknown. These colorful light and dark bands that surround Jupiter are created by strong east to west winds, traveling more than 335 miles per hour. Inside the atmosphere, diamond rain may fill the skies.
One of the most noticeable features of Jupiter is the Great Red Spot, seen on its surface. This is a giant hurricane-like storm that's lasted more than 300 years. At its widest, the Great Red Spot is roughly twice the size of Earth.
Jupiter spins faster than any other planet, taking under ten hours to complete a turn on its axis. The orbit of Jupiter is comparatively slow- it takes twelve years to orbit around the sun. Jupiter is named after the Roman king of the gods and ruler of the skies. His Greek counterpart is Zeus, god of the sky.
